{{About||the television news bulletins broadcast on Keshet 12 and Reshet 13|Israel Television News Company|its flagship bulletin|Hadashot (Israel Television News Company 8 pm IST bulletin)}} {{Infobox Newspaper | name = Hadashot | logo = | image = | caption = | type = Daily | format = | owners = Haaretz Group | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | staff = | foundation = March 1984 | political = | language = [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] | ceased publication = December 1993 | headquarters = | circulation = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = | website = }}
'''''Hadashot''''' ({{Lang-he|חדשות}}, lit. ''News'') was a [[Hebrew language|Hebrew-language]] daily newspaper published in [[Israel]] between 1984 and 1993.
==History== On 4 March 1984 [[Haaretz]] Group CEO [[Amos Schocken]] announced that a new daily newspaper, ''Hadashot'' was to be launched, with [[Yossi Klein]] as editor. It was one of the first Israeli newspapers to use colour printing.
The paper was soon hit by a scandal as it published details of the [[Kav 300 affair]] in violation of the [[Israeli Military Censor]]. Having decided not to join the [[Editors Committee (Israel)|Editors Committee]], ''Hadashot'' published a story stating that an investigative committee had been formed to look into the incident. As a result, the censor closed the paper for three days from 29 April 1984 for not sending the information about the article.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1081759.html Revisiting the photo that exposed a Shin Bet lie] Haaretz, 28 April 2009</ref> Although the paper was cleared of all charges in 1993, the closure damaged the momentum the paper had gained.
''Hadashot'' initially had a young, left-wing, anti-establishment image, and was written in youthful Hebrew, bordering on slang. The paper's approach was inconsistent; sometimes [[Yellow journalism|yellow]], sometimes highbrow.<ref>[http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Society_&_Culture/press.html The Israeli Press] Jewish Virtual Library</ref> In later years it became more conservative. Circulation remained low and at a press conference on 29 November 1993, Schocken announced the closure of the paper. The last edition was published on 29 December 1993, with the paper having made a cumulative loss of around $20 million.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb4803/is_199312/ai_n17442526/ No more news from Hadashot. (newspaper business closed)] Israel Business Today, December 1993</ref>
Senior journalists at the newspaper included [[Amnon Dankner]], [[Dudu Geva]], [[Dahn Ben-Amotz]] and [[Irit Linur]]. Photojournalist [[Alex Levac]] also contributed to the newspaper.
