In [[Belgium]], [[irreligion]] and [[atheism]] holds sway over a large portion of the population, numbering around 25-30%.<ref name="Special Eurobarometer 393 ">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_393_en.pdf |format=PDF |title=Special Eurobarometer 393 |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |accessdate=2015-03-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202023700/http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_393_en.pdf |archivedate=2012-12-02 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norc.org/PDFs/Beliefs_about_God_Report.pdf |title=Beliefs about God across Time and Countries |format=PDF|publisher=Norc.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-04}}</ref> Due to [[pillarization]] which is in place in Belgium, irreligious individuals and families who desire to receive counseling and celebration for life moments often go to institutions of [[organized secularism]], including ''secular organizations'' or ''liberal philosophical organizations'' ({{lang-nl|vrijzinnige levensbeschouwelijke organisaties}}, {{lang-fr|organisations laïques}}) which are headed and led by clergy-like officials known as "counsellors".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/20/world/europe/20belgium.html?_r=2 |title=Belgian Catholics Remain Anguished by Abuse |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2010-09-20 |accessdate=2012-06-25}}</ref> Religion has declined in Belgium, though Christianity still remains large among the Belgian population..<ref>{{cite news|title= Global Index of Religiosity and Atheism  |publisher= [[The Gallup Organization|Gallup]]|date=|url= http://www.winmr.com/web/files/news/14/file/14.pdf |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/religion/articles/2014/02/20/3949007.htm |title=What happened to Belgium? Lament for a Catholic nation – Opinion – ABC Religion & Ethics (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date= |accessdate=2015-03-10}}</ref>

