'''Virginia Fabella''', [[Maryknoll|M. M.]] is a [[Filipina]] [[theologian]] and [[Maryknoll Sisters of St. Dominic|Maryknoll sister]], known for her works in [[Asian feminist theology]] and [[postcolonial theology]].

== Biography ==
Fabella was born in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]. After graduating from the Assumption Convent in Manilla and receiving a BS from Mt. St. Vincent College in New York, Fabella joined the [[Maryknoll Sisters of St. Dominic|Maryknoll Sisters]] in 1952. She would later receive an MA in [[Religious studies|Religious Studies]] from the [[Maryknoll Seminary]] in 1980, a Certificate in [[Pastoral Studies]] from Union Theological in Chicago in 1988, and a [[Doctor of Ministry|DMin]] in [[Women's studies|Women’s Studies]] from [[San Francisco Theological Seminary]] in 1993. Her doctoral dissertation was entitled "The Development of Women's Theological Consciousness within the Ecumenical Association of Third World Theologians."<ref name=":0" />

In the 1970s, Fabella was the program coordinator for the [[Ecumenical Association of Third World Theologians]], later serving as its Asia Coordinator.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.maryknollsisters.org/sisters/sister-virginia-fabella/|title=Sister Virginia Fabella - Maryknoll Sisters|last=|first=|date=|work=Maryknoll Sisters|access-date=20 September 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Joseph2015">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bzneCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT241|title=Theologies of the Non-Person: The Formative Years of EATWOT|last=Joseph|first=M.P.|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-1-137-55054-5|location=New York|page=241}}</ref>

== Theology ==
Fabella is perhaps best known for her authored and edited works on Asian feminist theology and postcolonial theology. In terms of [[Christology]], Fabella has voiced that the maleness of Jesus is not a problem for Asian women, because by being male, "Jesus could more repudiate more effectively the male definition of humanity and show the way to a right and just male–female relationship."<ref>{{cite book|title=We Dare to Dream: Doing Theology as Asian Women|last=Fabella|first=Virginia|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4982-1914-3|editor1-last=Fabella|editor1-first=Virginia|location=Eugene, Oregon|pages=4|chapter=Christology from an Asian Woman's Perspective|ref=harv|orig-year=1989|editor2-last=Park|editor2-first=Sun Ai Lee}}</ref>

